{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"622ff665-72ba-43e6-8c39-6c259418ee8c","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Here's what the test confirmed:\n\n- `Span<nint> a = stackalloc nint[4];` — works, stored `42` and `nint.MaxValue` correctly.\n- `Span<nuint> b = stackalloc nuint[3];` — also works, stored `nuint.MaxValue` (`18446744073709551615`).\n- On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes (same as `long`/`IntPtr`).\n\nNative-sized integers (`nint`/`nuint`) are valid unmanaged types, so they work with `stackalloc` just like `int`, `long`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8be0f53-9923-4026-ac4b-016a45a70cdf","outputTokens":192,"requestId":"1443:2B8468:1367E30:15A6584:6A027944"},"id":"a4808a10-55f1-42d7-9934-a59ee09c8d46","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:18.721Z","parentId":"960f87df-665a-4a2e-a93b-9e16ca97da62"}
